      <IMG border="0" src="/images/stocking_up/41.jpg" width="142" height="144"><IMG border="0" src="/images/stocking_up/43.jpg" width="137" height="144"><IMG border="0" src="/images/stocking_up/46.jpg" width="143" height="143"></TD>
    <TD valign="top"><P>There are thousands of alcoholic drinks
      available to you. Clearly you can not be expected to stock all of this. So
      what do you do?
      <P>Your bar will grow as time goes on, but what are considered the essentials?
      There is no definitive answer to this, but below is what we consider to be
      a reasonably stocked bar.
      <P>Each bar should have a varied range of spirits, mixers and garnishes.
      <H4>Spirits</H4>
      <UL>
        <LI>Gin</LI>
        <LI>Vodka</LI>
        <LI>Rum (dark and light)</LI>
        <LI>Scotch whisky</LI>
        <LI>Bourbon</LI>
        <LI>Tequila</LI>
        <LI>Brandy/Cognac</LI>
        <LI>Vermouth (dry and sweet)</LI>
        <LI>Sparkling wine</LI>
        <LI>Dry white wine</LI>
        <LI>Dry red wine</LI>
        <LI>Triple sec</LI>
        <LI>Your choice of liqueurs</LI>
      </UL>
      <H4>Mixers</H4>
      <UL>
        <LI>Soda water</LI>
        <LI>Cola</LI>
        <LI>Ginger ale</LI>
        <LI>Tonic water</LI>
        <LI>Tomato juice</LI>
        <LI>Lots of different fruit juices</LI>
        <LI>Mineral water</LI>
        <LI>Grenadine</LI>
        <LI>Angostura bitters</LI>
      </UL>
      <H4>Garnishes/extras</H4>
      <UL>
        <LI>Olives (green and black)</LI>
        <LI>Maraschino cherries</LI>
        <LI>Lemons</LI>
        <LI>Limes</LI>
        <LI>Oranges</LI>
        <LI>Nutmeg</LI>
        <LI>Caster sugar</LI>
        <LI>Tabasco sauce</LI>
        <LI>Worcestershire sauce</LI>
        <LI>Sugar syrup</LI>
      </UL>
      <P>Oh yes and before I forget; ICE, and lots of it (crushed/cracked too).
      You can never have too much ice! When you think you have enough, make some
      more!! 
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>

